Senate, which is now pending in the House.

01:58.800 --> 02:03.280
I've just returned from Tennessee and I saw a lot of teachers, school people, and they

02:03.280 --> 02:05.880
are all interested in this subject.

02:05.880 --> 02:10.280
I thought Senator Yarbrough would be a mighty good senator who is very conversant with

02:10.280 --> 02:12.200
it to tell us about it.

02:12.200 --> 02:16.440
What tell us about the bill we got passed in the Senate, Ralph, and the need for it?

02:16.440 --> 02:22.240
Well, first of all, what is the situation today with reference to classrooms and teachers?

02:22.880 --> 02:29.080
Well, Estes, we have a shortage in the United States of about 135,000 trained school teachers

02:29.080 --> 02:32.720
and a shortage of about 140,000 classrooms.

02:32.720 --> 02:39.200
Now, that doesn't consider the million, 800,000 pupils who are in obsolete classrooms or

02:39.200 --> 02:42.960
crowded classrooms, too small, jammed up fire hazards.

02:42.960 --> 02:47.080
This is just classrooms where they're having to have two classes a day.

02:47.080 --> 02:51.640
Some students go to school half a day, some in the morning, some in the afternoon, which

02:51.640 --> 02:54.600
is a per system of education for the children.

02:54.600 --> 03:00.240
I believe the census will give us about 180 million people when it's completed.

03:00.240 --> 03:04.560
And I think it's estimated that 10 years and now we'll have better than 210 million

03:04.560 --> 03:06.560
people in the United States.

03:06.560 --> 03:07.560
Isn't that correct, Ralph?

03:07.560 --> 03:08.560
That's correct.

03:08.560 --> 03:10.960
In the cost of the classrooms, it's increasing.

03:10.960 --> 03:15.040
They tax burden for building these school buildings on the local homeowner and the local

03:15.040 --> 03:18.000
people has just about reached the limit.

03:18.000 --> 03:24.520
And to keep up this proper educational system, we've got to find new sources of tax revenue.

03:24.520 --> 03:28.440
Well, the future of our country depends upon the education of our youth, of course.

03:28.440 --> 03:33.160
Now, what does the bill provide in the way of granting aid to the states?

03:33.160 --> 03:38.160
They bill that passed in the Senate provides for a billion, nine hundred million dollars

03:38.160 --> 03:41.200
spent over two years with an optional provision.

03:41.200 --> 03:42.200
They share for the state.

03:42.200 --> 03:46.720
The Tennessee would be over twenty five million dollars a year.

03:46.720 --> 03:48.360
It is given to the state on an option.

03:48.360 --> 03:52.560
The state might spend it either for school buildings or for supplements to teach your pay

03:52.560 --> 03:54.760
or for any combination that the state wants.

03:54.760 --> 03:58.200
Well, we would get twenty five million a year in Tennessee.

03:58.200 --> 04:01.240
And it's also based upon the need of the state.

04:01.240 --> 04:04.640
And how much would Tennessee taxpayers have to contribute to that?

04:04.640 --> 04:06.240
About two and three quarter million.

04:06.240 --> 04:11.000
They don't need, in my state, for example, we would get sixty two million, the most of

04:11.000 --> 04:14.640
any state, but we have to contribute twelve million, some twenty percent.

04:14.640 --> 04:18.160
Based on need in Tennessee, they would contribute about twelve percent.

04:18.160 --> 04:20.160
And there are no federal strings attached.

04:20.160 --> 04:24.800
There's purely a grant in the age of the states to be spent either for supplementing teacher

04:24.800 --> 04:27.120
salaries or for construction of schools.

04:27.120 --> 04:28.120
Is that correct?

04:28.120 --> 04:29.120
Absolutely.

04:29.120 --> 04:30.120
Essentially keep over there.

04:30.120 --> 04:31.640
No federal strings on it.

04:31.640 --> 04:32.640
No federal control.

